channel.title: College educated, professional level, highly experienced developer available
channel.description:
Hi there. My name is Devin, I've recently finished up my BS in Computer Science and landed an internship at Intel here in Camas, WA.
Before I left the private server community to pursue my degree, I was the owner of the Eclipse servers, revisions 639 through 709. I'm sure information on my previous servers is available via a simple Google search.
I am here today to offer my services, free of charge, to someone who is willing and dedicated to a project worth doing. Not for my own gain, but simply for the fact that at one point in my life, this community was the only thing I had in my life worth counting on. So if your project is looking for a 6th year-experienced content developer or web developer, please post here to bump this thread and serious inquiries please send a personal message.

I have recently just made a private server but am still new to coding. do you know how to add a auto voting system to a 317 [PI]?
[/quote]and here’s the cake boom. possible ~10k CS degree and your test is adding auto voting to a 317 PI.

The having a CS degree does not mean you can do something like that. For one it has to do with multi-threaded services and dealing with web-linking and implementing into an unethical existing project. (That is more than likely not documented) Since everything in this community is a throw-together by its members, not everything is done in the most “straight forward” manner. I am a junior in my B of CS and still don’t have any educational experience with multi-threaded projects. (They start next semester)
The purpose of a CS degree mainly shows you have the ability to tackle software challenges to serve a purpose.
The fact is, they could do it - but their “effectiveness” of it would vary based on their experience with the given source.
I know 95% of allstar source like the back of my hand. Yes, it is ugly lol(the code, not my hand…).
SIUE student
[/quote]i thought comp sci is a math based. you know the basics but no programming. My school’s CS program has zero programming courses and just gives you high level math courses and theorys

You guys don’t have any OS, hardware, security, and other applied CS courses?
[/quote]no, we do, but it’s not in the CS program. We have individual courses available, mostly the ‘Computer Programming’ course but it’s just an associates and it’s nothing but programming classes. Then there is security courses that involve programming basics, and many more.[/quote]
